</p>
<p>The first URL - <code>/connect/facebook</code> - uses the Facebook provider service from the
oauth2-client library that we just setup. Its job is simple: redirect to Facebook
to start the authorization process. In a second, we'll add a "Login with Facebook"
link that will point here.</p>
<p>The second URL - <code>/connect/facebook-check</code> - will be the URL that Facebook will
redirect back to after. But notice it doesn't do anything - and it never will. Another
layer (the authenticator) will intercept things and handle all the logic.</p>
<p>For good measure, let's create a "Login with Facebook" on our normal login page:</p>
<p><div class="code-block-wrapper" data-code-block-guid="797ea77de9">
